explanation:
Reasoning for including each symbol (concise):

- OS_CHECK_POINTER
  - The macro can short-circuit the function (e.g. print an error and return). Its exact semantics determine whether the subsequent initializations/loops are executed at all — critical to decide if those operations are dead.

- os_fsinfo_t
  - The structure/type definition (and member attributes, e.g. volatile) is required to determine whether assignments to MaxFds/MaxVolumes/FreeFds/FreeVolumes are observable side effects (initialization vs. ordinary assignment), and thus whether removing them would alter program behaviour.

- memset
  - Zeroing filesys_info is a visible memory write. Knowing its semantics/implementation is necessary to judge whether the memset call is a required observable initialization or removable dead code.

- OS_MAX_NUM_OPEN_FILES, OS_MAX_FILE_SYSTEMS
  - The constants assigned to members affect the resulting state written to filesys_info. If their values or uses render the assignments redundant, that influences whether those assignments are dead.

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit
  - Initializes the iterator and (per implementation) may start transactions or otherwise change global state. Its behavior determines whether creating the iterator and subsequent iterations have observable effects beyond local increments.

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext
  - Drives the while loops. Its return behavior (how/when it yields true and any side effects) directly determines whether the loop bodies execute; essential to know if the loop increments are ever executed or are no-op/dead.

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy
  - Cleans up the iterator and may cancel/commit transactions or have other side effects. Removing the destroy call could change global state, so its semantics are needed to assess dead-code status of the associated code.

- OS_FileSysFilterFree
  - The filter callback controls which objects the iterator returns. Its predicate determines whether the loops will iterate (and thus whether the increment operations are executed), so its behavior is necessary for the analysis.

- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_FILESYS
  - The object-type identifiers select different object pools for iteration. They directly influence which objects are considered and whether each loop executes — needed to judge the loop bodies' observability.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The function returns this value. Need to know whether return value is significant for callers (observable behaviour) and whether alternative early returns (e.g. from OS_CHECK_POINTER) change outward behaviour.

- OS_GetMaxForObjectType, OS_GetBaseForObjectType
  - Used by the iterator init (implementation detail). They determine the iteration range; knowing them helps determine if the iterator will ever produce items (thus affecting loop execution and whether increments are alive).

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel
  - Called by iterator init/destroy (per the static graph). These functions may modify global transaction state — their side effects could make the iterator calls non-removable even if the loops produce no increments; hence required to assess whether code is dead.

- OS_printf
  - May be invoked by OS_CHECK_POINTER or other macros on error; printing is an observable side effect. Its involvement matters when deciding if the pointer check (and related code paths) are observable and therefore not dead.

Together these symbols cover the macros, types, constants, iterator functions and their callees whose semantics determine whether the writes, loops, and iterator setup/teardown in OS_GetFsInfo produce observable behaviour. Without them you cannot conclude whether removal of those operations would or would not affect program behaviour (the core of the MISRA dead-code rule assessment).
